{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}} {{Eastern name order|Enyedi Ildikó}} {{Infobox person | image = Ildikó Enyedi Press Conference On Body and Soul Berlinale 2017 03.jpg | name = Ildikó Enyedi | caption = Enyedi in 2017 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1955|11|15|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Budapest]], Hungary | parents = [[György Enyedi (geographer)|George Enyedi]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Film director, screenwriter | yearsactive = 1989–present }}
'''Ildikó Enyedi''' (born 15 November 1955) is a Hungarian film director and screenwriter. She has directed eight films since 1989. Her father, [[György Enyedi (geographer)|George Enyedi]], was a geographer and economist who played a major role in the long-term development of regional science.
==Career== Enyedi won the [[Caméra d'Or|Golden Camera]] award for ''[[My 20th Century|Az én XX. századom]]'' at the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name="festival-cannes.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/150/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: My 20th Century |accessdate=2 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> In 1992, she was a member of the jury at the [[42nd Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name="Berlinale">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1992/04_jury_1992/04_Jury_1992.html |title=Berlinale: 1992 Juries |accessdate=27 March 2011 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> Her 1994 film ''[[Magic Hunter]]'' was entered into the main competition at the [[51st Venice International Film Festival|51st edition]] of the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Giovanna Grassi, Tullio Kezich|title=Venezia, Stone in gara fra tanti " deb "|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/luglio/29/Venezia_Stone_gara_fra_tanti_co_0_9407296797.shtml|accessdate=21 October 2015|work=[[Corriere della Sera]]|date=29 July 1994}}</ref> In 2007, she was a member of the jury at the [[29th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name="Moscow2007">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2007 |title=29th Moscow International Film Festival (2007) |accessdate=22 April 2013 |work=MIFF |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421051129/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2007 |archivedate=21 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
Enyedi's 2017 film ''[[On Body and Soul]]'' premiered at the [[67th Berlin International Film Festival]], where it won the [[Golden Bear]].<ref name="Golden">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/berlinale-berlin-film-festival-2017-winners-full-list-1201992021/|title=Berlin Film Festival: ‘On Body and Soul’ Wins Golden Bear for Best Film|accessdate=18 February 2017|work=Variety}}</ref> The film went on to be nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]], representing Hungary.<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'ZURILLA|first1=CHRISTIE|title=At 89, James Ivory and Agnès Varda are the Oscars' oldest nominees|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-oscars-2018-nominations-90th-james-ivory-at-90-is-the-oldest-oscar-1516727367-htmlstory.html|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>
In 2018, she announced her next film would be an adaptation of ''The Story of My Wife'', about a man who makes a bet with his friend to marry the next woman who walks into the café where they are eating.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roxborough|first1=Scott|title=Lea Seydoux to Star in New Film From Director Ildiko Enyedi (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lea-seydoux-star-new-film-director-ildiko-enyedi-1084662|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref> The film was adapted from a novel by [[Milán Füst]] of the same name.
