{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot 006.jpg | title=The Bridge at Narni | artist=Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot | year=1826 | type=Oil on paper mounted on canvas | height_metric=34 | width_metric=48 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=Paris | museum=[[Musée du Louvre]] }}
'''''The Bridge at Narni''''' (in French: ''Le pont de Narni'') is an 1826 painting of the [[Ponte d'Augusto (Narni)|Ponte d'Augusto]] at [[Narni]] by [[France|French]] artist [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot]]. The painting is currently on display at the [[Musée du Louvre]] in [[Paris]].
The painting is a product of one of Corot's youthful sojourns in Italy, and, in [[Kenneth Clark]]'s words, "as free as the most vigorous [[John Constable|Constable]]". It was painted in September 1826, and was the basis for the larger and more finished ''View at Narni'', which was exhibited at the [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] of 1827, and is now in the [[National Gallery of Canada]], [[Ottawa]].
The view was not a novel one: in 1821 Corot's teacher, [[Achille-Etna Michallon]] had drawn the same scene, as had Corot's friend Ernst Fries in 1826. Corot's study is a reconciliation of traditional and [[plein air]] painting objectives:
''So deeply did Corot admire [[Claude Lorrain|Claude]] and [[Nicholas Poussin|Poussin]], so fully did he understand their work, that from the outset he viewed nature in their terms....In less than a year (since his arrival in Rome) he had realized his goal of closing the gap between the empirical freshness of outdoor painting and the organizing principles of classical landscape composition.''<ref>Galassi, Peter, ''Corot in Italy'', page 168-70. Yale University Press, 1991.</ref>
== See also == * [[Narni]], an ancient hilltown and ''[[comune]]'' of [[Umbria]], in central [[Italy]]
